               <history>
                  <origin>
                     <origDate calendar="Hijri-qamari" notBefore="1663" notAfter="1664">Regnal year
                        16 (of Aurangzeb, 1663-64)</origDate>
                     <origPlace>India</origPlace>
                  </origin>
                  <provenance>
                     <p>Dating from the 17th century, the manuscript belonged to Muḥammad Aḥsan
                        Allāh Khān, Sayyid Muḥammad and Mīrzā Muḥammad Khiṣāl before being acquired
                        by Richard Johnson between 1770 and 1790. That it was then acquired by a
                        further owner, probably in India, is certain because Johnson's acquisition
                        notes are partially covered over by a pasted strip carrying an unrelated
                        Persian inscription. It was therefore not part of the Johnson collection
                        which was sold to the East India Company in 1807, but instead was acquired
                        at a later date by H.G. Raverty after whose death it was sold with two other
                        manuscripta in 1907 by his widow to E.G. Browne and thence to the E. J. W.
                        Gibb Memorial Fund (See <title>A descriptive catalogue to Oriental MSS. belonging
                        to the late E.G. Browne</title>. Cambridge, 1932, p. 142).</p>
                  </provenance>
                  <acquisition>
                     <p>Presented to the India Office Library by the Gibb Memorial Fund on <date
                           when="1927-06-23">23 June 1927. </date></p>
                  </acquisition>
               </history>
